Introduction

The Nationwide Readmissions Databse (NRD) from the Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project includes data on inpatient discharges with ICD 10 codes for diagnoses and procedures, length of inpatient days, patient demographics, payment methods, hospital costs, as well as data from readmissions and deaths in hospital. This database addresses the lack of information on hospital readmissions in healthcare data. Unweighted, the NRD data has approximately 16 million discharges. Weighted, this estimates approximately 33 million discharges. The discharge data is from 30 states, accounting for 59.6% hospitalizations in the U.S. Thymomas are rare malignant tumors of the anterior mediastinum, with an age-standardized incidence of 0.13 to 0.15 per 100,000 population at risk in the United States. Surgical resection of the thymus is the recommended therapy for thymomas. However the exact method of resection, open thymectomy (open resection of thymus) or minimally invasive thymectomy (percutaneous endoscopic resection of thymus), has been a point of controversy. This project will address the question: of patients diagnosed with disorders of the thymus, are open thymectomies or minimally invasive thymectomies more common?

Methods

The Nationwide Readmission Data from 2020 was acquired from the Healthcare Cost and Utilization Project as a CSV file. It was then read in specifically for columns related to deaths, hospital IDs, and the ICD 10 diagnosis and procedure codes. Using the âdimâ function, there were a total of 16,692,694 observations and 67 columns after reading in the columns associated with the variables listed above. The âstrâ and âsummaryâ functions showed that deaths were coded as integers 0 or 1, with 1 indicating death. Hospital ID numbers started from 71001 to 74803. ICD codes for diagnoses and procedures were character variables. The data was then extracted specifically for ICD 10 diagnosis codes related to thymic disorders into a dataset called filtered_data, which resulted in 26,473 observations. This procedure required processing the dataset in chunks of 50,000 due to the large size of the total dataset, and the loop function was used for each chunk. Frequencies of different types of thymic disorders and methods of thymectomies were calculated from this extracted dataset called filtered_data. Methods of resection were then stratified by type of thymic disorder and visualized into a bar chart.

Preliminary Data

#Read in Data

library(data.table)


nrd_2020 <- fread("/Users/erinyu/Desktop/NRD Datasets/NRD_2020_Core.csv", 
                  select = c("V3", "V14", paste0("V", 17:56), paste0("V", 61:85)))

#Extract diagnoses related to disorders of the Thymus

library(data.table)
library(kableExtra)

search_values <- c("D150", "E320", "E329", "G7000", "G7001", "C37", "C7A091")
search_labels <- c("Benign neoplasm of the thymus",
                   "Persistent hyperplasia of thymus",
                   "Disease of thymus unspecified",
                   "Myasthenia Gravis without acute exacerbation",
                   "Myasthenia Gravis with acute exacerbation",
                   "Malignant neoplasm of thymus",
                   "Malignant carcinoid tumor of thymus")


chunk_size <- 50000
total_rows <- nrow(nrd_2020)
output_file <- "filtered_data.csv"  


header <- colnames(nrd_2020)
empty_df <- data.table(matrix(ncol = length(header), nrow = 0))
setnames(empty_df, header)


fwrite(empty_df, file = output_file, append = FALSE)


search_value_counts <- numeric(length(search_values))


for (start_row in seq(1, total_rows, by = chunk_size)) {
  
  end_row <- min(start_row + chunk_size - 1, total_rows)
  
  
  chunk <- nrd_2020[start_row:end_row, ]
  
  
  if (nrow(chunk) > 0) {
    
    subset_chunk <- chunk[, paste0("V", 17:56), with = FALSE]
    
    
    if (ncol(subset_chunk) > 0) {
     
      for (i in seq_along(search_values)) {
        search_value_counts[i] <- search_value_counts[i] + sum(as.matrix(subset_chunk) == search_values[i])
      }
      
     
      match_rows <- apply(subset_chunk, 1, function(row) any(row %in% search_values))
      
    
      if (any(match_rows)) {
        chunk_filtered <- chunk[match_rows, ]
       
        fwrite(chunk_filtered, file = output_file, append = TRUE)
      }
    }
  }
}

#Table of Types of of Thymic Disorders

results_df <- data.table(
  "Condition" = search_labels,
  "Count" = search_value_counts
)


results_df %>%
  kbl(caption = "Counts of Thymus-Related Conditions") %>%
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover", "condensed", "responsive"),
                full_width = FALSE, 
                position = "center")

#Method of Resection Stratified by Thymic Disorder

library(ggplot2)
library(data.table)


diagnosis_codes <- c("D150", "E320", "E329", "G7000", "G7001", "C37", "C7A091")
diagnosis_labels <- c(
  "Benign neoplasm of the thymus",
  "Persistent hyperplasia of thymus",
  "Disease of thymus unspecified",
  "Myasthenia Gravis without acute exacerbation",
  "Myasthenia Gravis with acute exacerbation",
  "Malignant neoplasm of thymus",
  "Malignant carcinoid tumor of thymus"
)
resection_codes <- c("07TM4ZZ", "07TM0ZZ")
resection_labels <- c("Percutaneous Endoscopic Resection", "Open Resection")


results_list <- list()


for (i in seq_along(diagnosis_codes)) {
  for (j in seq_along(resection_codes)) {
    
    count <- sum(apply(filtered_data, 1, function(row) {
      any(row[paste0("V", 17:56)] == diagnosis_codes[i]) &
      any(row[paste0("V", 61:85)] == resection_codes[j])
    }))
    
    
    results_list[[length(results_list) + 1]] <- data.table(
      Diagnosis = diagnosis_labels[i],
      Procedure = resection_labels[j],
      Count = count
    )
  }
}


results_df <- rbindlist(results_list)


ggplot(results_df, aes(x = Diagnosis, y = Count, fill = Procedure)) +
  geom_bar(stat = "identity", position = position_dodge(width = 0.8), width = 0.7) +
  labs(title = "Methods of Thymus Resection Procedures by Diagnosis",
       x = "Diagnosis",
       y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#4CAF50", "#FF7043")) +  
  theme_minimal(base_size = 14) +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold", hjust = 0.5),
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1, size = 10),
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 12),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size = 14, face = "bold"),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    legend.title = element_blank(),
    legend.position = "top"
  )

Conclusion

The most common types of thymic disorders were Myasthenia Gravis with and without acute exacerbation (804 and 2883, respectively). Benign neoplasms and malignant neoplasms occurred at similar frequencies (224 and 221, respectively). After extracting data containing diagnoses of thymic disorders, procedure counts for open thymectomies (open resection of thymus) versus minimally invasive thymectomies (percutaneous endoscopic resection fo thymus) were collected. Overall, minimally invasive thymectomies were more common than open resection thymectomies (109 counts and 85 counts, respectively). When stratifying the methods of open resection by type of thymic disorder, minimally invasive thymectomies were more commonly done in less severe diagnoses including benign neoplasm of the thymus, disease of thymus unspecified, myasthenia gravis (with and without acute exacerbation), and persistent hyperplasia of thymus. Open resection thymectomies were only increased in malignant neoplasm of thymus. This makes sense, since malignant neoplasms are more aggressive and may require thorough resection, requiring the open approach.
